A yorker to end, it is jammed out to point.
From around the wicket, it lands on middle, defended.
Outside off, Steven Smith shuffles across and leaves it alone.

Was probably in two minds there, Marnus Labuschagne! Slightly shorter and on off, Marnus Labuschagne looks to pull but does not go through the shot. It goes towards mid on for one. He probably wanted to bail out in the end.
Shaheen now goes full and outside off, no swing for him, it is pushed to covers. The wicket just looks dead today. Probably the flattest it has been in this game.

FOUR! More runs! Marnus Labuschagne moves into the 80s and the partnership is now two short of 100. On the pads, Marnus Labuschagne works it through square leg, the new ball races across the turf and into the fence. The outfield is still fast despite the rain.
A dot to end but the damage was done earlier on. On middle, Smith stays back and blocks it onto the ground.
NO BALL! Naseem has overstepped! Shorter and outside off, Smith slashes but misses.
FOUR! Clipped away! That is one area you do not want to bowl to Smith! On the pads, this is clipped through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Goes back to bowling it on a length and around off, defended.
FOUR LEG BYES! First poor delivery of today by Pakistan! On the pads, this is tickled fine on the leg side and it races away to the fence. It is actually off the pads as the umpire signals leg byes.
Good delivery! Goes wide of the crease and angles it into middle. Smith defends. Both the bowlers have begun well with the second new ball.
Back of a length and on off, Steven Smith pushes it to covers.
Naseem Shah (13-2-54-0) comes to bowl now.

BEATEN! That is another lovely delivery! Length and on off, this lands and then moves away. Marnus Labuschagne is beaten as he tries to block. A lovely over with the second cherry by Shaheen comes to an end.
This one is a harmless nut, outside off, left alone.
Just outside off, Marnus Labuschagne watches it go to the keeper. Good stuff from Shaheen, has started really well with the new cherry.
On middle, defended.
BEATEN! That is a beauty! This lands on middle, and then moves away. Marnus Labuschagne does not put in a big stride forward and tries to block but is beaten.
Starts off with a length ball, slanting away from off. Left alone.

The second new ball is now available and we feel, Pakistan will take it immediately. Yes, they do take it. The new ball is probably the best chance for Pakistan to pick a wicket. Shaheen Afridi comes into the attack.
This is darted on the pads. Steven Smith tickles it through the fine leg region for a couple of runs.
Floated, on a length, around off. Steven Smith blocks it off the back foot.
On a length, around off. Steven Smith keeps it out.
Edged but safe! Slower through the air, on a length, around middle. Marnus Labuschagne backs away to drive but it goes off the outside edge past the slip fielder for a single.
Tosses it up, outside off. Marnus Labuschagne drives but Nauman Ali dives to his left and stops the ball.
Flatter and on off. Marnus Labuschagne blocks it off the back foot.
A single to end as Marnus Labuschagne eases it down to long on.
On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
On the stumps, it is kept out.
On middle, blocked.
On middle, this is pushed down to long on for one.
On middle, this is worked through square leg for one.
Quicker and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne goes back and gets his bat down in time. Once again the back foot approach. Working well though on this slow surface.
On middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for one.
Slower, it lands on off, hint of turn away. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend but it goes off the outer half towards point for one.
On middle, this is kept out.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
On off, this is pushed to covers.

Floats it up on off, blocked. The wicket seems the best to bat on today. There were a few balls which were spinning on Day 3 but it seems like a road on Day 4. Just nothing in it for the bowlers so far.
A little too straight, this is clipped down to fine leg for one.
Tossed up on off, Marnus Labuschagne lunges and keeps it out.
On middle, blocked.
Flatter and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne stays back and keeps it out.
On middle, this is worked to square leg.
So just the boundary from the over then! This is given nice flight and it is bowled on off, Smith pushes it to covers.
Another one tossed up on off, Smith pushes it to covers.
On middle, defended.
Flatter and drags the length back on middle, blocked.

FOUR! Whipped away! Very nicely played. This time the length is a little too full. Smith gets close to the ball which does not allow it to turn, he works it against the spin through md-wicket to help Australia avoid the follow-on.
On middle, fuller, this is worked to mid on.
On off, Labuschagne works it with the turn to mid-wicket.
First run for Smith today! On middle, he pushes it down to long on for one.
The broom is out, Marnus drags it from outside off and through mid-wicket for one.
Another one tossed up on off, blocked.
Impact outside off! This is floated up outside off. Marnus Labuschagne looks to play the paddle sweep but misses to get hit on the pads.
Flatter and on off, Marnus Labuschagne goes back and defends. Saw this a lot on Day 3 where ML was happy to go back and defend. Does that here too.
Who will start from the other end? Sajid Khan it is.
Just the single from the first over on Day 4! Good stuff from Nauman. Disciplined stuff we should write. On middle, Smith lunges and keeps it out.
Another loopy ball, relentlessly hitting just the one spot is Nauman. Smith is happy to block it out.
Good start by Nauman! This is on the stumps again, nicely looped. Blocked.
Slows it up, bowls it on off, Smith pushes it to covers.
Flatter and on middle, Smith hangs back and blocks.
Straightaway a single to get things underway on Day 4! Marnus Labuschagne steps out and eases it down to long off for one.

We are set for Day 4 to get underway! The players of Pakistan have made their way out to the middle. Steven Smith and Marnus Labuschagne are at the crease. Nauman Ali will start proceedings with the ball. Here we go..

UPDATE - 1 pm IST (7.30 am GMT) - We finally have some good news, folks! The play is set to start at 1.30 pm IST (8 am GMT). A total of 67 overs to be bowled today. Also, the play can be extended until 6.15 pm IST (12.45 pm GMT). We hope that the weather and light stay fair, so that we get all the scheduled overs post Lunch break.

The last time when Pakistan cricket had a problem in drying the water on the outfield, there were choppers called for that purpose. Maybe they can try that yet again, especially around the bowler’s runup which is the reason of concern right now.
UPDATE - 12.15 pm IST (6.45 am GMT) - The umpires will have another inspection at 12.45 pm IST (7.15 am GMT). Also, early Lunch has been taken! Stay tuned as we bring you further updates.

There’s still no official news about the Lunch break. We are assuming early Lunch will be taken and that should be the case but nothing as of now. Maybe, they are hopeful of some cricket before the break. It would surely come as a surprise if that happens.

UPDATE - 11.30 am IST (6 am GMT) - The umpires are done with their inspection but they don't look satisfied with the playing conditions. Hence, there will be another inspection at 12 pm IST (6.30 am GMT). Any play before Lunch seems unlikely at the moment.

For those who follow Indian domestic cricket, Syed Mushtaq Ali winners and Vijay Hazare runner-ups, Tamil Nadu has failed to reach the Quarter finals of the Ranji Trophy, whereas Mumbai have made it through for the first time in the last few years. The few other teams are Karnataka, Jharkhand and Bengal.

Also, there is yet another player pulling out due to mental health issues and this time it is the Bangladesh great, Shakib Al Hasan who will not be featuring in the Tests against South Africa. He was struggling even in the recently concluded Afghanistan series but he decided to be a part of that after having a word with the BCB President. Also, he has decided to concentrate more on white-ball cricket. It is not easy nowadays with the bio bubble and everything. Mental health of players seriously needs to be considered and we really wish a speedy recovery for Shakib.
The inspection is going on and the players are also seen warming up. Something tells me, we aren’t far away from live action.

Also, England’s 12-man squad has been announced for the first Test against the Windies. Foakes is making a return, we might see Lees making his debut. No Ollie Robinson as he has been ruled out so Saqib Mahmood might just get a go which means there could well be two debutants.

In other news, the hosts of the Women’s World Cup, New Zealand might just get their first points of this year’s tournament. They are in a very comfortable position needing just over 60 with 9 wickets in hand against Bangladesh. However, anything is possible as we saw that in their last game against the Windies.

We should have had the first ball by now but the wait continues. The groundsmen are doing their job and the clouds are also passing by. The umpires will have an inspection at 11 am IST (5.30 am GMT). We hope that the action begins soon. Stay tuned for further updates.

Just to confirm, we are surely not going to start on time. The teams are yet to leave from their hotel, not sure when that is going to be happen, the only confirm news we can give right now is the start has been delayed!

Let’s now talk about the weather! It has rained the whole night and the outfield has taken a real pounding. It’s quite wet and a timely start looks doubtful. The only positive at the moment is it is not raining currently so fingers crossed. Also, the Australian team hasn't left the hotel yet.

Hello and welcome to the coverage of Day 4 of the first Test between Pakistan and Australia. This game has moved at a snail’s pace and all the interventions haven’t helped either. It seems to be heading towards a draw but as they say, in this part of the world, things can change pretty quickly. Have to say it is Australia who are in a better position at the moment , they trail by just over 200 and have 8 wickets in hand. Pakistan on the other hand, will feel, a wicket here and they would surely have a chance of taking a lead as the middle order is not totally reliable. The first session can prove to be an important one.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Pakistan would be regretting slightly for picking only two frontline pace bowlers. Shaheen Afridi and Naseem Shah bowled with a lot of fire but did not offer much control. Both the frontline spinners too were inconsistent with their lengths. We're expecting the trend of bat dominating ball to continue on Day 4 also. EARLY START on Monday as well. The first ball will be at 10.15 am IST (4.45 am GMT) but as usual, our build-up will begin in advance. Goodbye for now!

As a visiting team, you won't mind such surfaces to start your tour. It was tough on the bowlers of Australia but their batters have made full use of the helpful conditions. A 156-run opening stand set a strong platform and that would have eased the nerves in the dressing room. Usman Khawaja nearly had a perfect homecoming, falling short of his century by 3 runs. The bromance of Steven Smith and Marnus Labuschagne is blooming in the middle and their alliance didn't allow any opening to the Pakistan bowlers in the evening session. Both have looked settled and in sync with the pace of the pitch.

The game situation is quite simple to read. The bowlers continue to toil hard and the batters are feasting on a batting paradise. Two wickets in the entire day's play - that too mainly due to the error in judgement (Warner) and poor shot selection (Khawaja). Australia have eaten out a major chunk of the deficit which is now down to 205 runs. Two more days left in this Test and unless this pitch turns into a minefield all of a sudden, we are heading towards a high-scoring draw.

Update 5.12 pm (11.42 am GMT) - As expected, it's STUMPS ON DAY 3! In this part of the world, the light never improves as the evening approaches and with the drizzle arriving, this was inevitable. We lost a few overs on Day 2 and now got only 72 overs bowled on Day 3.

Update 4.46 pm IST (11.16 am GMT) - No update from the ground. It seems that the conditions have not improved much, as expected. It's looking unlikely that we will have any more play on Day 3. Still, stay tuned for the official update.

Update 4.24 pm IST (10.54 am GMT) - The players are going off for BAD LIGHT! The light has deteriorated considerably and maybe it has gone below the reading that was taken on Day 2. Babar Azam wanted to use pace from both ends and that may have been the reason also. Stay tuned, we will keep you informed.
A near-yorker this time, around leg at 144.1 kph, Steven Smith flicks but finds square leg.
Angling down the leg side, left alone.

THAT'S A BEAMER! First warning for the bowler. Shaheen Afridi perhaps was aiming for the yorker but it turns out to be a full toss, around leg and Smith turns to keep it out towards square leg. Called a no ball and Shaheen apologizes too. On closer look, that full toss was dipping below the waist. Anyway, it was a dangerous ball, especially under the fading light.
Slightly fuller this time, around off at 133.3 kph, Smith defends it from the back foot.
Targets the off stump with a length ball, Smith is behind the line in defense.
Angles in a length ball, around middle and leg, Marnus Labuschagne clips it behind square leg and picks up a single.
Shaheen steams in from 'round the wicket and darts in a length ball on off, Marnus defends it from the back foot.
Pace from both ends. Babar Azam is testing the umpires here as the light is fading. Shaheen Afridi to have a go. 14-2-46-0 are his figures so far.
Slightly short and on off, Labuschagne punches it in the gap at covers and collects a single.
Delivers it on a length and close to off, Marnus Labuschagne plays nice and late as he keeps it out safely to covers.
Slip comes out and goes to short mid-wicket.
Uses the angle of the bowler and works a length ball to mid-wicket.
Around off, angling in from a good length, Marnus Labuschagne defends it from the back foot.

FOUR! That's a glorious shot! Short in length and outside off, plenty of width available, Marnus Labuschagne watches it onto his bat and smacks it through cover-point. The fielder chases but the ball teases him on its way to the boundary line.
Begins his spell with a length ball around off, Marnus Labuschagne covers the line and defends it to covers.
Naseem Shah (12-2-49-0) is brought back into the attack now. One slip and a gully in place.
FOUR! Smashed! Poor line from Nauman, delivers it full and down the leg side, Steven Smith turns and clobbers it past the leg gully fielder for a boundary.
Around leg, defended down towards short leg.
Loopy and full around leg, Smith drives it down through mid off. Sajid Khan pulls it back near the fence and the batters get a couple of runs.
Another flatter delivery, short and landing on the rough outside leg, Smith gets back and plays it down to short leg.
Flatter and shorter, landing outside leg, Smith goes back and wears it on his pads.
Flighted and full, around leg, Smith lunges, clears his front leg and defends it back.
Tossed up on off, this is pushed to mid off for one more.
Flatter and on middle, kept out.
On middle, defended.
A single as this is worked through mid-wicket.

FOUR! Nice and fine! Lovely batting! On the pads, Marnus just uses the pace and clips it past the leg gully fielder and into the fence. That brings up the 10th 50-plus stand in Tests between this pair of Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith.
On middle and leg, this is worked through square leg for one.
Down the leg side, left alone. Very predictable bowling from Nauman.
Another one down the leg side, this is tossed up. Marnus Labuschagne looks to sweep but misses.
Yet again this is bowled down the leg side, Marnus Labuschagne has no problem in padding it away.
On the pads, Marnus Labuschagne kicks it away again, it goes towards fine leg but no runs taken as the shot was not offered.
Down the leg side, it is padded away.

Marnus takes another blow on his right forearm. Full and flighted, landing on the rough outside leg, Marnus Labuschagne tries to sweep but misses. It shoots up and pings him below the elbow. That part of Marnus' hand is bruised. He took a blow earlier also, against the bowling of Naseem Shah while trying to pull him.
Very full and close to off, Smith gets forward and across to jam it down near his front foot. The ball rests on the popping crease there.
Full and wide outside off, Smith reaches out to drive but finds the cover fielder.
Sajid goes quicker through the air, the length is a bit short and Smith camps back to block.
Loopy and full, around off and spinning in, Smith lunges and defends it from the inner half of his blade.
A touch short and on middle, Marnus goes on the back foot and tucks it to square leg for one.
Fuller and around off, Marnus Labuschagne goes down and sweeps it in front of square leg for a couple of runs.
A single to end then. This is on off, it is pushed through covers for one.
On middle, kept out.
On middle, this is pushed to covers.
On middle, defended.
Down the leg side, left alone.
Two more! Marnus Labuschagne is scoring quickly now. On the pads, this is worked fine on the leg side for two.
A single to end as this is swept through square leg.
On middle, blocked.

FOUR! Yet another boundary in the over! On off, fuller in length, Marnus Labuschagne goes down on one knee and hits it through square leg. No one in the deep. Also, fifty for the best batter in this format, currently. These were very unfamiliar conditions for him and it was going to be a big challenge to tackle the spinners. He was shaky at the start but now looks in full flow. Can he make it into a big one here?
Tossed up nicely and on off, Marnus Labuschagne blocks.
On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one more.
FOUR! Does not start off well. This is down the leg side. Marnus Labuschagne stands back and hammers it past short fine leg for a boundary.
Sajid Khan is on again. Change of ends for him. So, Iftikhar Ahmed was used to just get the ends changed for both the frontline spinners.
Another one tossed up and on off, kept out well.
Floats it up on off, it's defended.
This one stays low! On middle, it does not bounce much. Smith gets his bat down and blocks.

'Catch it' is the shout but it is hit well enough! Smith comes down the track, does not quite get to the pitch of it but still goes ahead with the lofted shot behind the bowler. Clears mid on and gets a couple.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Flatter and on off, this is pushed to covers.
This is not a promising sign. The groundsmen are getting ready with the covers. For now, the umpires are staying but maybe, the rain is not far away. Nauman Ali gets a change of ends.
A little too straight again, this is clipped to mid-wicket.
On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Flatter and on middle, defended.
On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Really good fielding! Shorter and on off, Marnus Labuschagne guides it past point. Sajid Khan runs after it, dives forward to pull the ball back and saves a run for his side.
Fuller and on off, this is pushed to mid off.
Change! Iftikhar Ahmed is on now! Not sure why Nauman Ali is removed.
Fuller and on off, Marnus pushes it to covers.
Floats it up on off, defended.
That is not where Rizwan will want him to bowl! Down the leg side, left alone.
Rizwan really liked that! Wants Sajid to bowl there and even tells him that. Floated up on off, blocked.
On middle, defended.
Tossed up on off, this is worked with the turn to square leg for no runs.

Sajid Khan to bowl from the other end! Mike Haysman (on air) shares the information that the umpires went for Bad Light last evening as Pakistan wanted to bowl pace. The conditions again are very similar and maybe, that's the reason, Babar Azam has not started with one of his seamers from this end.
Flatter and on middle, defended.
Shorter and on the pad, this is clipped through square leg for one.
Marnus Labuschagne comes down the track again, this time the length is shorter. He defends.
FOUR! That is a lovely shot! Marnus Labuschagne steps out, gets to the pitch of the ball and also makes room. He strokes it through the gap between covers and mid off for a boundary.
Flatter and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne lunges and keeps it out.
Tossed up on off, this is pushed to covers.

We're back and so are the players. Get ready for another session. Two world-class batsmen at the crease and Pakistan would be trying to remove both of them before the close of day's play. This is going to be fun. The artificial lights are also switched on. The breeze has picked up intensity and the forecast is for some rain. Let's hope it stays away. Nauman Ali to start proceedings with a slip and short leg in place...
... DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

Two wickets in the afternoon session, on this docile surface, can be taken as a big success for Pakistan. That said, both the wickets were gifted to them. David Warner misjudged a length and lost his stumps while Usman Khawaja tried to be adventurous on 97 and gloved it to short leg. One wicket apiece for the Pakistan frontline spinners and the hosts will be expecting more of the same from them in the evening session. A word of praise for Naseem Shah as well who bowled a fiery spell and tested the batters with his pace and short-pitch bowling. For Australia, the reliable Steven Smith and Marnus Labuschagne are at work and a lot will be expected from their alliance. The deficit for Australia at the moment is 254 runs. Do join us at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT) for the last session of the day.
A single to end the session! Shorter and on the body, this is pulled down to fine leg for one. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 3!
Shorter and angling away from off. Marnus lets it be.
Shorter and on off, Marnus Labuschagne pushes it to covers.

Some excitement but not sure why? Shaheen goes over the wicket and bangs it short. Smith pulls it through mid-wicket. They take one and Marnus Labuschagne wants another one but is sent back. The throw is towards the keeper who deflects it back onto the stumps. Marnus Labuschagne though is well in. IT IS ACTUALLY REFERRED UPSTAIRS! Rizwan did put in an appeal and that is why the excitement. Replays show Marnus Labuschagne is safe.
Goes short again but down the leg side. Left alone. A few words by Shaheen to Smith.
FOUR! Smart batting! Short and on off, Smith gets on top of the bounce and guides it past gully and down to the vacant third man region for a boundary.
A single to end the over! Just the one from it! On the pads, Smith looks to flick, it goes off the pad towards fine leg. A leg bye is taken.
Fuller and on off, Smith strokes it to covers.
Flatter and on middle, Smith defends.
Close! Steps out but Nauman shortens the length. Smith though does well to keep it out.
Tossed up on middle, defended.
On middle, Smith works it to short leg.
Short but down the leg side, Marnus Labuschagne swivels on the back foot but without using his bat. Lets it go to the keeper.
Delivers it short and wide outside off, Smith plays late and guides it down to third man for a run.
Shaheen goes fuller, to surprise the batter, it's around middle and Smith defends it back from the outer part of his blade.

FOUR! Third time lucky! Shaheen Afridi continues to bowl short as a part of plan, around off, there is not much pace on this surface so Steven Smith easily rides the bounce and this time pulls it wide of backward square leg for a boundary.
Action replay of the previous ball. Shaheen digs in another short ball, Smith once again pulls it with full control but finds backward square leg.
Helped away! Short and around off, Smith stands back inside the crease, gets on top of the bounce and just eases his pull shot to backward square leg.
Outside off, shorter, this is slapped to the fielder at covers.
Floats it on off, this is pushed to covers.
Well played in the end! This lands on middle and then turns away. Marnus Labuschagne reaches out to defend but then seeing the turn, opens the face of the bat and guides it down to third man for two.
Solid! On off, Marnus comes forward and plays it back to the bowler.
Flatter and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne lunges and defends.
A quick run! On middle, Steven Smith works it to mid on and gets to the other end.
A good over by Shaheen comes to an end! The last ball is outside off, Marnus Labuschagne lets it go to the keeper.
Relentless stuff! Makes the batter play again, goes full and on off, Marnus Labuschagne strokes it to covers.
Bringing in all his variations now! A slower one on middle, Marnus Labuschagne defends.
Goes back to bowling it on a length and on off, defended. Really good from Shaheen making the batter play on almost every ball.
That is a sharp bumper! Really good. Marnus Labuschagne does well to duck under it. No ball though, Shaheen oversteps in the attempt to put in that extra effort.
Good shot but for no runs! Fuller and on off, this is driven but to mid off.
That is a good leave! This lands outside off and comes back in. Marnus Labuschagne leaves it.
Tossed up and on middle, Smith puts in a good stride forward and plays it with a straight bat.
Another one tossed up on middle, Smith plays it back to the bowler.
Smith comes down the track again, does not quite get to the pitch of the ball. Defends it.
Floats it up on off, this is pushed to cover.
Flatter and on middle, defended.
Smith steps out, he works it to mid-wicket for no runs.
Fuller and on off, Smith takes another single as this is pushed towards mid off.
Down the leg side this time. Smith looks to flick but misses.
Outside off, Smith has no interest in playing that.
Fuller and on off, this is pushed to covers for one.
Angled into middle, this is kept out nicely.
Good length and on off, defended.
Drags his length back a shade, around off, Smudge goes on the back foot and defends it solidly. A successful over for Nauman Ali!
Floated and around leg, Smith lunges and blocks.
Loopy and full around middle, Smith defends it back.
Loopy and full around off, defended off the front foot. Called a no ball.
Steven Smith walks in next. He is going through a lean patch, not in terms of runs but in terms of 'big runs'.

OUT! TAKEN! Pakistan put in a loud appeal but the umpire is unmoved. Pakistan review, Usman Khawaja is the man in question. Has he fallen three short of a ton? YES, HE HAS! Heartbreak for Usman Khawaja on his return to the home soil. UltraEdge shows there is something as it passes the glove. That is an excellent review from the hosts and now they have both the openers back in the hut and have one relatively new batter and one very new at the crease. Nauman Ali strikes now. Usman Khawaja will be gutted with himself. He played so, so well. Really not sure why he tried playing that shot. He is very confident about it but it is always a risky stroke on a wicket that is offering turn. This lands outside off, turns back in. Khawaja looks to play the reverse sweep. This one turns back in and there is also extra bounce. It hits the gloves, as the replays showed later, and lobs to the short leg fielder where it is taken by Imam-ul-Haq. Pakistan can now capitalize here. Australia are still a long way behind.
Fuller and on middle, this is worked towards mid on for one.
On middle, Marnus Labuschagne keeps it out.
Three more and Marnus Labuschagne retains strike! Outside off, Marnus Labuschagne strokes it through covers for three. 200 up for Australia!
Floats it up on off, Marnus Labuschagne pushes it to mid off.
This one is pushed through, a lot quicker. Marnus Labuschagne defends.
Shorter and on off, ML guides it to point.
FOUR! Controlled stroke! This is around off, fuller in length, Marnus Labuschagne plays the reverse sweep with great control through backward point for a boundary.
On off, this is pushed through covers for one.
Flatter and on off, this is pushed to covers.
He is now a boundary away! On the pads, this is worked through square leg for a single.
This lands outside off and turns back in. Usman Khawaja looks to guide it on the off side but gets an under edge as it drops in front of first slip.
Slightly shorter, a little bit of turn, it is worked through square leg for one.
This time puts in a good stride forward and defends this one on middle.
Quicker and on middle, stays a touch low. Marnus Labuschagne keeps it out off the back foot.

FOUR! That has been nailed! It was hit so hard! Also, a cracking sound came off the bat. On middle, Khawaja goes down on one knee and hammers the slog-sweep through mid-wicket. Good over for the Aussies.
Shorter and outside off, Usman Khawaja pushes it to covers, Marnus Labuschagne wants a single but is sent back.
Another single! On middle, Marnus works it through mid-wicket and takes one.
Moves to 91 now as he works this through mid-wicket for one.
FOUR! Hit hard! Catch it was the cry but that was hit quite straight. Khawaja comes down the track and gets to the pitch of the ball, he hits it hard down to the long on fence. He moves into the 90s.
Tossed up on middle, defended.
Floats it up on the pads, Marnus Labuschagne plays it onto the ground with soft hands.
Angled into the pads, this is worked on the leg side.
Loopy ball and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne keeps it out.
Lands this one middle, wanting it to spin square. Marnus Labuschagne blocks.
Slightly fuller this time and outside off, Marnus strokes it to covers.

That is beautifully bowled! That spun sharply! This lands around off, it turns away sharply. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend but is beaten. Really good start from him and it will make him feel a lot better. He has gone for runs but will fancy his chances bowling to a right-hander.
Change! Nauman Ali is on now. He has bowled just 4 overs so far.
On middle, this is worked through square leg for one.
Marnus Labuschagne comes down the track but fails to get to the pitch of it. Blocks it.
Quick run! On middle, this is worked to mid on for one. The fielder did have a shy but misses. Would not have mattered.
On middle, Khawaja works it to the left of the bowler.
Very full and on middle, this is jammed back to the bowler.
Flatter and on middle, defended.

FOUR! Respect the good balls, put away the bad ones, that is exactly how Marnus Labuschagne is playing at the moment. He gets another gift, on the pads, he does not let it go as he works it fine on the leg side for a boundary.
Another one on the off pole, Marnus Labuschagne blocks it.
Attacks the stumps again, slightly fuller than usual, ML plays it to covers.
On the stumps, defended.
Good comeback! A real effort ball on off, Marnus Labuschagne stands tall and looks to defend but it hits the splice.
FOUR! Puts this one away! Just a little bit of width on offer and that is enough. It is played through point for a boundary by Marnus Labuschagne.
A single now as this is pushed through covers.

And again! Marnus Labuschagne plays back to a delivery that was very full, could have driven it, it was almost that full. On slow wickets, one might get away with it but if there is a little bit of zip, you are bound to get out. This is on middle, Marnus Labuschagne gets his bat down in time and blocks.
Floats it up on off, defended.
Tossed up outside off, turns back in. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend but it goes off the inner half towards short leg.
Looks to play the reverse sweep, this turns in from outside off, Marnus Labuschagne hits it onto the ground and to the slip fielder.
On off, this is pushed through covers for one.

Drinks break. Australia are steady after losing Warner. Khawaja has looked unfazed while Marnus Labuschagne is still new at the crease and trying to come to the terms of the pitch. Pakistan have bowled better in the afternoon session. Sajid Khan has stuck to disciplined lines while Naseem Shah has bowled with a lot of fire. They would love to have a few more wickets in the next hour.
Goes wide of the crease and angles it into the off pole. Defended.
Solid! Back of a length and on off, Marnus Labuschagne blocks.
Slightly shorter and on middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for one. No ball signaled.
Good length and on middle, defended.
Fuller and on middle, this is driven nicely but to mid on.

That has hit Imam! He has copped a few blows in the last few overs. This one though would have hurt. The pull shot was hit hard, it was middled but it hits short leg and goes behind for one. He is off now, no short leg in place at the moment.

The crowd liked that! Naseem bangs it short and on the body, Marnus Labuschagne is not one of those who would shy away from the challenge. He goes to pull but misses to get hit on the right forearm. He seems in a little pain.
Usman somehow keeps this one out! This is fuller, Khawaja stays back, he though gets his bat down in time and blocks.
Tosses it up on off, this is pushed to mid off.

Needed to react better there! Imam-ul-Haq needs to stay lower for longer, he came up early there. On middle, this is flicked uppishly. Goes between the legs of Imam at short leg and through square leg for one.

That is a risky stroke! Especially on a wicket which is turning, yes, slow turn but turn. This lands outside off and spins back in. Marnus Labuschagne moves to the leg side and guides it through point for one.
Slows it up, it lands outside off and turns back in. Marnus Labuschagne blocks from the back foot.
Just wide! This is tossed up and on off, Khawaja pushes at it with hard hands, it goes uppishly but wide of silly point for one.
Extra bounce! Bent his back on this one. It lands and then takes off. Hits the splice of the bat as Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend and goes on the off side.
Good stuff from Naseem! Yet another one on the off pole, Marnus pushes it to covers.
Good length and on off, defended.
That is a good nut! Length and on off, this one skids through. Marnus Labuschagne is late in getting his bat down, it hits the bottom part and goes behind.
Just like that! Length and on off, Marnus Labuschagne keeps it out.
Naseem really needs to make the batter play a lot more! This is on a length and outside off, left alone.
The physio comes out. He examines Imam-ul-Haq who was hit near the neck region. All seems fine and we resume.

Shorter and outside off, Khawaja looks to cut, he ends up chopping it on the off side as it comes slowly off the surface. It actually hits Imam, at silly point, on the back of the neck. Mohammad Rizwan walks up to Imam, smiles and leave. In comes Babar, who jokingly hits him on the helmet.
Gives it air again and lands it on middle, Usman Khawaja plays it back to the bowler.
Quicker and on middle, Khawaja stays back and keeps it out.
Tossed up on off, Khawaja defends.
Quick run! Tossed up outside off, turning back in. Marnus Labuschagne looks to drive it through covers but this one turns back in, it goes off the inner half through mid on for one.
Outside off, this is pushed through covers for one.
Back of a length and on off, Marnus Labuschagne stands tall and defends.

FOUR! Glorious shot to get off the mark! Yes, it is a half volley but still has to be put away. Full and on off, this is driven through covers by Marnus Labuschagne for a boundary. Elegant, just sit back and admire.
Three in a row now as this is again bowled well outside off and Marnus leaves.
There comes the trademark Labuschagne leave to this ball outside off.
Just no bounce there! Outside off, left alone. This one almost goes along the ground to the keeper.
Good start by Naseem! On middle, Khawaja works it through mid-wicket for one.
Flatter and on middle, Marnus Labuschagne goes back and blocks.
This is tossed up on off, Marnus Labuschagne works it to mid-wicket.
Marnus Labuschagne is the number 3 batsman.

OUT! TIMBER! Stop the press, Pakistan have managed to break the mammoth opening stand. The crowd here comes to life and it is Sajid Khan who strikes and gets rid of the dangerous Warner. David just misread the length and the line. He chose the wrong ball to cut. This is flatter and around off, it comes in with the angle at 84.4 kph and also stays a touch low. Warner stays leg side and looks to manufacture a square cut but this goes past his bat and hits the stumps. Sajid is absolutely pumped up. Is this the opening Pakistan needed? Australia are still 320 runs behind. Chance now for Pakistan to apply pressure.
Shorter and outside off, this is pushed through covers for one.
Floats it up and on middle, Khawaja blocks.
Flatter and on middle, defended off the back foot.
Short and on middle, Khawaja pulls it through square leg for one.
Another one on the stumps, defended.
On off, kept out.
Yet another bumper, ducked under.
Angled into middle, Khawaja works it to mid-wicket.
A real effort ball, short and on the body, gets some nice bounce. Khawaja ducks under it.
Floats it up and on off, Warner blocks. Tidy from Sajid.
Quicker and on off, David pushes it to covers.
Lovely delivery! Slows it up and bowls it on off, Warner waits and then defends.
Flatter and on middle, defended.
Flatter and outside off, Khawaja has enough time to go back and play it through covers for one.
Shorter and on off, this is pushed through covers for one.

FOUR! EDGED AND BETWEEN THE KEEPER AND THE SLIP FIELDER! That would not have carried to first slip anyway. 150 up for Pakistan and the frustration continues for Pakistan, especially Shaheen. Lovely delivery. This lands just around off and holds its line. Khawaja has a poke at it away from the body, it goes off the outside edge between the two and into the third man fence.
Around off, Usman hangs back and guides it to point.
Fuller and on off, Khawaja strokes it to covers.
Yet again makes the batter play by attacking the stumps. Negotiated quite easily as Khawaja pushes it towards cover.
Angled into the middle pole from wide of the crease. Defended.

Bangs this short, this one stays a touch low. Warner looks to pull, he gets an under edge onto the thigh pad. It deflects to the right of Mohammad Rizwan, the keeper, and they jog across for a single.
Floats it up nicely and lands it on middle, blocked.
Quicker and on middle, Khawaja stays back and blocks it out.
Fires this one on off, Warner strokes it to covers.
Flatter and on off, Warner pushes it to covers.
FOUR! Desperate dive but in vain! Outside off, Warner waits and then guides it down towards third man. The backward point fielder hares after it, dives but his effort goes in vain.
Shorter and outside off, Warner cuts but finds point.
Targets the off stump with a length ball, Khawaja once again is solidly behind the line in defense.
Hurls across a length ball outside off, Usman Khawaja takes his front leg forward to cover the line and shoulders arms.
Back of a length, close to off and angling in, Khawaja is right behind the line and defends it solidly.
A sharp short ball, around off at 139.5 kph, Usman Khawaja sways away from the line of fire.
Lands it on a length around off, getting it to angle towards the off stump, Usman Khawaja stays back and blocks it down.
Bouncer around leg, it's an easy duck for Usman Khawaja.
Fires it full and around leg, Usman Khawaja nudges it through backward square leg for one.
Short and wide outside off, Khawaja cuts but finds the point fielder.
Flatter and quicker, around off, Usman goes on the back foot and then brings his bat down in defense.
Drags his length short and serves it on off, Warner goes back and punches it to sweeper cover for a run.
Tossed up, landing full on middle, Warner defends it off his front foot.
Loopy and full around middle, Khawaja drives it down to long off for a run.
Sajid Khan to continue from the other end.
Slants it in, on a length around off, Warner defends it to covers.
Extra bounce again. On a good length around off, Warner hangs his bat out in defense and it goes off the upper half to point.
Shaheen Afridi bends his back to go short, it's around middle at 136.7 kph, David Warner hops and defend it down on the surface.
This one is landed in the blockhole, Warner is equally up to the challenge as he digs it out safely.
Usman Khawaja loves it there. Fuller in length, around middle and leg, Khawaja plays a wristy flick to deep square leg for a run.
Right on the money. It's on a length, around off and angling in, Khawaja does well to keep his eyes on the ball as he keeps it out. That one stayed slightly low.

Welcome back. The players are returning on the field. Australia have built a strong platform and it's all about extending this good start forward. Pakistan would be banking on their spinners in this session to create some magic. So far, they have been a bit too short and wide and during the break, the think tank would have pointed that out. Shaheen Afridi (6-1-25-0) to start...
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

It's been a strong start for the Aussies. Usman Khawaja was the aggressor in his 'home' Test and scored quite fluently. David Warner took his time to settle down but is now looking at his best. Pakistan had a couple of opportunities to dismiss Usman but Fawad Alam dropped him on 22 at gully and then there was a half-chance when Khawaja was on 62 but Mohammad Rizwan was late with his reflexes. It appears to be another batting day in Rawalpindi. Do join us at 1.10 pm IST (7:40 am GMT) for the post-Lunch session.

The conditions were overcast, the ball was used only for one over, Shaheen Afridi and Naseem Shah expected to breathe fire, the Aussie openers would have definitely felt the pressure. But, after the first 15 minutes or so, it was clear that the pitch doesn't have anything for the bowlers. There was hardly any movement for the seamers and while there was some spin, it was on the slower side. Safe to say now, after seeing the Pakistan team bowl as well, that this pitch is as dead as a dodo.

A fruitful session for the Aussies - one they needed to boost their confidence after spending two days on the field. 133 runs scored in the morning at a run rate of 4.16. Dominance won't be the wrong word to describe Australia's progress thus far.
A decent over by Iftikhar Ahmed! A couple to end the session! Outside off, this is guided through point for two. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 3!
5 dots in a row! Can Iftikhar Ahmed close it out well? This is on off, Warner pushes it on the off side.
Make that 4! Fires it on the stumps, Warner shows the full face of the bat and plays it onto the ground.
Better from Ahmed! Three good balls to begin this over. On middle, kept out.
Flatter and on middle, this is pushed out.
On middle, this is pushed back to the bowler.
Floats it up on middle, Khawaja defends.
Angled into the pads, this is worked to mid-wicket.
Darts this one on the stumps, Khawaja stays back and blocks.
Floats it up on middle, Usman Khawaja blocks.
On off, Khawaja pushes it to covers.
Flatter and on middle, this is defended.
On the stumps, Warner defends it back to the bowler.
FOUR! Deft again! Third boundary in the over! Short and outside off, Warner hangs back and once again guides it past point. This races away to the fence. He is now nearing Khawaja.
Flatter and on middle, defended.
Could have easily been another boundary! This is short and wide outside off, Warner slaps it but to covers. He would feel he missed out there.
FOUR MORE! Tickled away! Not the start Iftikhar Ahmed was looking for. On the pads, Warner plays it fine and this one races away to the fine leg fence.

FOUR! Put away! Fifty for Warner. Started off very slowly but now is into his elements. He enjoys playing against Pakistan, averages over 100 and now is just improving that. A big score is on the offing here. Shorter and outside off, he plays it late and down towards third man for a boundary.
A single to end! Outside off, this is pushed through covers for one.
Good comeback! Tosses it up on off, defended.
FOUR! Hit with disdain! That was a hit-me ball. Short and wide outside off, Warner slams it through covers for a boundary.
Angled into the pads, Warner works it fine on the leg side for two. He is into the 40s.
Comes down the track but the length is shortened. Warner looks to defend but gets hit on the pads.
Floats it up on off, defended.
Yet another delivery, tossed up nicely and on off, defended.
On middle, Khawaja works it to short leg.
Nicely flighted and on off, Khawaja manages to defend.
Tosses it up on off, Khawaja keeps it out.
FOUR! Splits the gap brilliantly! That is hit hard! On middle, out comes the sweep, it is nailed through square leg between the two fielders in the deep, for a boundary.
Tossed up on off, Khawaja keeps it out.
Shows the full face of the bat now and plays it back to the bowler. Really good over from Sajid Khan. Pakistan need a lot more of such tight overs to build pressure.
On the stumps, Warner plays it back to the bowler.
Tosses it up on middle, kept out.
On middle, defended.
Now pushes this one through on off, Warner guides it to point.
Well played in the end! Warner comes down the track but does not get to the pitch of it. Defended.
Floats it up on off, defended. 11 runs from this over.
FOUR! This is nailed! He does not shy away from playing the reverse-sweep again because it is his strength. This is outside off, he hits it through backward point and this one races away too.

Was that a chance? Well, it was a very tough one, if it was. Rizwan just got up a little too early! Outside off, Khawaja looks to play a reverse sweep, it goes off the gloves and as Rizwan was getting up, it hits him on the flap of his pad. Had he stayed low, it may have stuck in his gloves.
Flatter and on off, defended.

Good effort from Shaheen! Saves one for his side. Warner now goes down on one knee, plays the paddle sweep fine on the leg side. Shaheen makes a lot of ground to his left and saves a run for his side.
FOUR! Whipped away! This is full and on the pads, Warner flicks it hard through mid-wicket and it races away to the fence.
Flatter this time and on off, Khawaja blocks.
Another loopy delivery on off, Khawaja pushes it to covers.

Just past the edge! That is a lovely ball. Gives it a lot more flight, lands it around off, draws Khawaja forward to defend and then gets the ball to turn away. It just goes past the edge. That ball had everything but not the edge.
Shorter and outside off, Khawaja pushes it towards cover.
Shorter now and on the pads, Warner works it through square leg for one.
Angled into the pads, this one goes on with the arm. Warner defends for the turn, he gets an inside edge onto the pads which lands safe.
Flatter this time and lands it outside off, Khawaja stays back and blocks.
Gives it air and lands it on off, blocked.

Two more and the 100 is up! This is an outstanding start for the Aussies and it has come up in a quick time too. A half volley outside off, it is driven through covers for two to take them up to that score.
Skips down the track now but does not get to the pitch of the ball, it's defended in the end.
FOUR! The reverse sweep comes out and it is played to perfection. Khawaja plays those brilliantly. This is outside off, he hits it behind point and it races away.
Just wide! This lands outside off and turns back in. Khawaja leans forward to defend, it goes off the inner half wide of short leg.
Swept away nicely! On middle, Khawaja hits it through square leg and takes one.
On middle, defended.
Slows it up and lands it around off, Khawaja comes forward and looks to defend, it goes off the outer half to covers.
Gives it flight and lands it on middle, defended.
FOUR! Put away! Short and outside off, Khawaja plays it late and gets it through backward point for a boundary. Really good shot. Waited and then played it brilliantly.
Flatter and on middle, Khawaja stays back and defends.
Good leave in the end! This lands well outside off and turns back in. Warner covers his off pole and leaves it alone.
No run in the end! Warner steps out and pushes it towards cover. The fielder fumbles but no run is taken.
Pushes this one through and bowls it on the stumps, Warner plays this off the back foot.
Flatter and on off, Warner blocks it out.
Flatter this time and lands it on off, Warner pushes it to covers.

FOUR! Warner does not want to let him settle! Straightaway goes after the left-arm spinner. This is tossed up on off, Warner plays it with the spin, he drags it through mid-wicket and welcomes Nauman with a boundary.
Change! Nauman Ali comes on for the first time in this game now.
A touch short and on off, Usman Khawaja punches it down to mid off. A dot ball to end the over.
Flatter around off, defended towards point.
Turning away from the batter, Usman Khawaja lunges to defend but is beaten.
Quicker and on off, staying low, Khawaja defends it by keeping his eyes on the ball.
Shortish and on off, Khawaja gets back and mistimes his square cut to point.

FIFTY FOR KHAWAJ! A happy homecoming for him. Short and wide outside off, Usman cracks it to cover-point for a single. The fielder fumbles slightly and another run is taken. Dropped on 22, Usman Khawaja has not looked behind since then.
A half-tracker, around the rib cage, Khawaja pulls it a bit uppishly but wide of leg gully. A single as the ball travels to deep backward square leg.
Short but down the leg side, Usman lets it be for the keeper.
Bumper on middle, at 137.6 kph, Khawaja ducks.
FOUR! Clever from Khawaja. Short and around off, at 141.1 kph, Khawaja steps back and lofts it behind backward point for a boundary.
Naseem Shah bangs it short once again, around off, Warner gets on top of it and pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Digs it in short, around middle and leg, Warner pulls and it goes on one bounce to leg gully.
A 6-3 field. Leg side dominating here. Naseem is going to attack Warner on middle and leg.
On the stumps, Khawaja plays it onto the ground.
FOUR! Up and over! That is a beautiful shot! Steps out, gets to the pitch of it and with the turn, lofts it wonderfully over the mid off fielder for a boundary. Very elegant. Classy.
On the stumps, defended.
Warner comes down the track and works it towards mid on for one.
Another one floated up on middle, kept out.
On middle, Warner defends it.
Angled into middle, Khawaja works it to mid-wicket.
Shorter and down the leg side, Warner nudges it down to fine leg for one.
Now brings out the full one and on off, Warner pushes it to mid off.

Gets hit on the body again! Goes short, not a lot of bounce. Warner looks to pull but misses to get hit on the body. A long followthrough by Naseem there. Warner picks up the ball and hands it to Naseem along with patting him on the shoulder. Well, it is a no ball but it still hurts. In fact, Warner might even be thinking, why did that no ball have to be in THIS over? It means another extra ball to face from an on-fire Naseem.

Warner cops a blow there! A friendly banter too between him and Naseem, it did look friendly. Short and on middle, Warner does not pick it early. He just takes his eyes off the ball in the end and gets hit on the body.
Another one on the stumps, Warner pushes it to covers.
Good length and on off, Warner pushes it to covers.
Gives it air and lands it on the stumps, Khawaja pushes it to covers. 14 from the last two overs. Pakistan need to stem the run flow here.
Floats it up on middle, Khawaja blocks.
Slower through the air, once again lands and then comes slow off the surface. It is pushed to covers.
Slightly shorter and on off, Warner pushes it wide of mid off and takes one.
Shorter and on off, this is pushed to covers.

FOUR! Raining boundaries now off the bat of Warner. Another one short and outside off, quite a slow surface so such deliveries sit up to be hit. Warner rocks back and cuts it through point. He quickly moves into the 20s after a slow start.
Runs continue to flow for the Aussies! This is on the pads, Warner looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and rolls on the leg side. A leg bye is taken.
This is where you bowl to Warner, length and on middle, Warner defends. Need to cramp him for room. He is someone who feeds on width.

FOUR! And again, Naseem Shah has not learned from the last ball that this is not where you bowl to Warner. He just loves staying leg side. This is once again short and outside off, Warner hops and cuts it through cover-point. Another boundary.
FOUR! Cracked away! That has been nailed! Short and outside off, width on offer. Warner feeds on such deliveries. He slaps it through point for a boundary.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Good length and on off, Warner blocks.
Warner retains strike! He comes down the track and gently works it towards mid on.
On middle, nicely flighted. Defended.
Sees this one tossed above the eye line. Warner steps out and hits it hard but straight at the bowler.
On the pads, this is worked to mid-wicket.
This pitches around off, turns away. Slow turn. Warner adjusts and keeps it out.
Well bowled! Tosses it up and lands it on middle, defended.
Fuller and outside off after the delay. Left alone.

What happened there? Naseem Shah is limping a bit after delivering the last ball. A few Pakistan players gather near the popping crease at the bowler's end. Seems some loose soil has come out. The umpires want it to be fixed and have also decided to take the Drinks break. A good first hour for Australia. They have avoided any hiccups and their openers have been largely untroubled. Pakistan got one chance to remove Usman Khawaja but Fawad Alam dropped a sitter at gully. The pitch continues to look unresponsive, for the Pakistan bowlers as well. Australia could not have asked for a better strip to start this tour. Can their batters make full use of the batting-friendly conditions?
Well played in the end! On the shorter side, this one rises on Khawaja. He takes one hand off the handle and defends.
That is a beauty! Excellent use of the angle! Lands it on off and then slants it away. Khawaja is beaten as he tries to block.
Another one on the shorter side, Khawaja pushes it to covers.
On off, the length is dragged back a touch. Defended.
Starts off with a full one on middle, Khawaja strokes it to mid on.
Change of ends for Naseem Shah! He has bowled 4 overs so far for 17 runs.
On off, this is blocked.
Slightly shorter and on off, Warner pushes it to covers.
Angled into the pads, Warner manages to defend.
Floats it up this time and lands it on off, Warner lunges and keeps it out.
Big turn and also extra bounce. Shorter and outside off, this lands, spins away and also takes off. Warner looks to cut but is beaten. Yes, turn but slow turn.

Good shot! Makes good use of the feet. Skips down the track and works it against the turn through mid-wicket. Naseem, at mid on, hares after it, he bends down to pick the ball but does not do so. Recovers well but three taken till then. Naseem just went down a little too early.
And again, with full control, hangs back, gets on top of the bounce and pulls this short one towards fine leg for one. Khawaja was interested in a second for a little while but turned back.
No yorker this time though, Shaheen goes length and on off, Khawaja, who is already hanging back, blocks it from within his crease.
Three bumpers in a row. Shaheen really bowling with a lot of steam here. Khawaja once again though ducks. Be ready for a yorker now, Shaheen has a really good one.
Goes short again, aimed at the head. Khawaja lets it go over him.

FOUR! Wonderfully timed! He was so much in control of this shot. Khawaja seemed to be ready for this and the 50 is up for Australia and they have got it up in no time! Short and on middle, Khawaja hangs back and pulls it through square leg. This one races away to the fence.
Back of a length and on off, Khawaja hangs back and defends.
A touch short and close to off, Warner defends it from the back foot to the off side.
Tossed up, full and around off, Warner uses his feet to smother the spin and defends it back.
Skidding down the leg side, Warner allows it through to the keeper.
Lunges to a full ball around off and defends it with a firm bottom hand.
Quicker this time, flat and short on middle, David goes back and nudges it to mid-wicket.
Full and floated around off, Warner presses forward and pushes it to covers.

FOUR! This is glorious! Two boundaries in a row and this will only frustrate Shaheen. This is full and on off, Khawaja creams it through mid off and this races away. Australia are off to a brilliant start. End of an action-packed over, it could have had a wicket in it but instead goes for plenty.
FOUR! Adding salt to the wound. As it happens, a boundary after a chance goes down! Full and on the pads, Khawaja clips it through square leg for a boundary.

DROPPED! Fawad Alam should have taken that. Pakistan should have had their first wicket. A life for Khawaja. That was the perfect set-up from Shaheen. Bangs the last one short, pushes the batter onto the back foot and now goes full, shaping away. Khawaja is rooted to his crease, he looks to drive but does so ahead of his body, it flies off the outside edge and Alam at gully spills it, it goes behind for two.
A good bumper, Khawaja ducks under it.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Fuller and on the pads, Warner looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and rolls towards fine leg for one. Leg bye signalled. Also, it is a no ball.
Another short one, Warner this time is ready for it and ducks under.
Good nut to end! Bowls this quicker and gets the line and length right. On middle, Khawaja goes back to play it but gets his bat down in time.
On middle, Khawaja is solid in defense again.
Gives this one air, it is on off, the ball lands and spins away but it is slow turn. The batter has enough time to go back and push it to covers.
A little too short this time, tries to push it through but bowls it shorter than he would have liked. Warner stays back and pushes it towards covers for a run.
Now tosses it above the eye line, slightly fuller though on middle, Khawaja pushes it toward mid off for one.
Good start by him, gets a little bit of turn! This is tossed up on middle, it lands and holds its line. Khawaja blocks.
Change! Sajid Khan is on now!
So 5 dots after the boundary on the first ball. Good from Shaheen. Good length and on middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Now this one just does not rise! Shorter and outside off. Warner leaves it alone. It goes on the bounce to the keeper.

Once again catches Warner off guard! Goes short and Warner is taken by surprise yet again. Not sure if he is taken by surprise by the change in length or the bounce here. Warner looks to fend it away by taking his eyes off the ball. It goes off the splice but lands safely on the leg side.
Yet another one on the fuller side, Warner prods forward and guides it to point.
Angled into the pads, Warner works it to mid-wicket.
FOUR! That is a strong punch! It races away on this turf! Slightly fuller this time and on off, Warner pushes it through covers. No stopping that.
Three harmless deliveries in a row to end! Outside off, not played at.
Yet another nut outside off, Khawaja shoulders arms to this one.
Outside off, Khawaja does not fiddle with it.
That is nicely played! This comes in with the angle, Khawaja hangs back and works it late through square leg. Two taken.
Now gets the line right, it is around off, the length though is way too short. Warner stands tall and pushes it towards cover for one.

Naseem has not been very accurate with his lines and lengths. He has bowled well only in patches so far. Starts off with one on the pads now, Khawaja looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and rolls on the leg side. A leg bye is taken.
Fuller and outside off, Warner once again does not move his feet a lot. Looks to push at it, it goes off the inside edge on the leg side. A maiden then by Shaheen.
Back of a length and on off, Warner pushes it to covers.
Another one angled into the stumps, it is kept out nicely.
This stays a tad low! Good length and on middle, defended.

That is brilliant from Afridi! The two Pakistan bowlers are really generating good pace off the wicket. They are rushing the two batters. Warner seemed uncomfortable now with this short one. He is taken by surprise. It is on the body. Warner somehow fends it away on the leg side. It was in the air for a moment but lands safely. The surface seems to have quickened up a touch or maybe because the ball is new.
Good length and on middle, Warner rocks back and blocks it out.

FOUR! Shah is going for runs! Second boundary in the over, not totally convincing but a boundary! Outside off and shorter. Khawaja could have left it alone, he instead hangs his bat out, opens the face of the bat late and guides it past gully.
So this has been the story so far for Naseem, he has followed a wide one with one on the stumps. This is on off, Khawaja hangs back and blocks it out.
Goes back to bowling it outside off, left alone.

FOUR! Khawaja somehow manages to get that to the boundary! That was quick, a sharp bumper and well directed too. Khawaja had no time to move out of the way. He somehow manages to pull it through, he was not watching the ball throughout but connects and it races away to the square leg fence.
Now bowls it outside off, Khawaja won't be playing at those.

EDGED BUT LANDS SHORT! Soft hands and also the slow nature of this wicket. Even the new balls aren't going to hang. Length and on off, this is angling in from around the wicket, lands and straightens. Khawaja is squared up as he tries to block. It goes off the outside edge and lands well short of second slip.
Shaheen bowls yet another testing over. Good stuff! Ends with a length ball on off, defended.
A little too straight this time, Khawaja clips it through square leg for one. Let the ball come to him there, played it nice and late.

An appeal but that is going over! That is outstanding from Shaheen! That came as a surprise, not only for us but for Khawaja too. Shaheen has been taking the ball away so far but this time gets it back in a long way from outside off. The length was a tad short. Khawaja leaves it alone expecting it to move away. It hits his back leg. An appeal but turned down. No DRS taken. This will now build doubts in the mind of the batter as to which way he will be swinging the ball.
Another one down the leg side, once again Shaheen looks to bowl the magic ball but no movement yet again. Khawaja looks to flick but misses.
Looks to bowl that magic delivery! Tries to swing it away from the leg pole, this one goes on with the angle and it ends up down the leg side. Good take by Rizwan.
Nice movement again! Length and outside off, shaping away. Khawaja covers his off pole and lets it be.
A dot to end but a good over for the visitors! Naseem goes full and on middle, this is played back to the bowler.
Angled into the pads, Khawaja works it through square leg for one.
Good length and on off, defended.
Now goes around the wicket, goes full, almost a yorker but on the pads. Khawaja tries to flick but misses. It goes off his pads to fine leg for a couple of leg byes.
Did you know? Naseem Shah made his Test debut in Australia in 2019. At 16 years and 279 days, he became the youngest Test debutant in Australia.

FOUR! That is glorious from Khawaja! That is a shot that will boost his confidence. This time Naseem gets his length wrong, goes very full and on off, Khawaja shows the maker's name and strokes it past mid off. It races away to the fence.
Naseem has not got his line right so far. This is yet again well outside off. Khawaja does not fiddle with it.
Another beauty to end a lovely over from Shaheen! He's also getting the ball to move away nice and late. This is on off, this one lands and moves away. Warner is beaten as he tries to defend.
Another one fuller and on middle, Warner does not put in a good stride forward and just pushes it to mid on.

EDGY FOUR! A lucky boundary for Warner to get off the mark. Another tentative push. Length and outside off, moving away. Warner hangs his bat out well away from the body, it goes off the outside edge past gully and down to the fence.

That is a beauty! Also, that is the kind of length which causes problems for Warner early on as he plays from the crease early in his innings. It is fuller and on off, shapes away late. Warner's feet are glued to the crease, he pushes at it away from the body. Luckily for him, gets beaten.
This is quite wide outside off, Warner lets it go to the keeper.
Shaheen goes full and on middle, looking for some shape away from the left-hander. None available. Warner plays it back to the bowler.
Shaheen Afridi to bowl from the other end!
A dot to end! A tidy start by Naseem but a harmless one. The last ball is also a little too wide outside off, Khawaja leaves it alone. Not a lot of movement for Naseem.
Perfect! Length and it lands around middle and on off. Khawaja plays it late and on the off side. This is the line he needs to bowl on a consistent basis.

5 now! This though is a lot close to the off pole, not close enough to make the batter play though. Naseem is getting the ball to move away, he needs to land it around middle. For now, he is bowling just outside off.
Make that 4 leaves in a row, yet another delivery well outside off, nipping away off the wicket. Left alone.
The length is really good, the line though is just a little wide. Khawaja makes his third leave in a row. Also, Naseem has overstepped, no ball called. First run of the day.
Good beginning from Naseem Shah! No loosener, up for it right from the word go. The second one is fuller and outside off, gets this one to shape away a little. Khawaja leaves it alone.

That is a really good start by Naseem Shah! Bowls it in a very good channel and also gets some zip off the surface which probably won't last for long. This starts around the 5th stump channel. Comes back in a tad. Khawaja shuffles across and leaves it alone.

Time to get going! The players are on the field. David Warner and Usman Khawaja are ready to fight. Naseem Shah to start proceedings. It's overcast but the light is decent. Three slips and a gully waiting. Here we go...

Just an update about the weather! It is quite cool and cloudy. There is a forecast for rain but later on in the day. This though should be really good conditions to bowl for the pacers, especially with the ball being new. The likes of Shaheen Afridi and Naseem Shah could well be deadly if they get it right. Testing times ahead for the Aussie batters.

We've talked a lot about the docile nature of the pitch, but in cricket, you should never drop a verdict unless both teams have batted and bowled at least once. It could easily come down to the quality of both the departments of these teams, so let's sit back and watch what the Pakistan bowlers extract from this pitch. Of course, there will be wear and tear, rough marks and footprints but are they enough to turn this sleeping 'batting' beauty into a minefield?

Welcome back, folks! Australia will be batting today. This is one aspect of the game that tests the foreign teams the most in the subcontinent. A lot of preparation goes into the way you want to brave the challenge of the alien conditions and it's now time to put everything to practice. It won't be wrong to say that the performance of Australia this morning, afternoon and evening will lay down the marker for this tour. A very important day of this Test series is coming our way shortly. Stay tuned...

Signing off thinking of the legacy Shane Warne has left behind. A deep thought on Twitter. 'Shane Warne. Declaring early whilst the rest of us think this is madness for one final time.' Still can't believe he's no longer with us. Sad.

Stumps on Day 2! This was always on the cards with the light not expected to improve at this time of the evening. Yet another satisfying day for Pakistan. They could have batted with more purpose but you need to give credit to Australia here. Despite not getting regular wickets, they made sure that the home team had to sweat for every run. The plan to declare was to have a go at the Aussies late in the day but that didn't happen. Australia will get some rest before Day 3 and will come out with a fresh mindset. The pitch has not played a lot of tricks and with proper application, the touring team can also succeed. EARLY START on Sunday. The first ball will be at 10.20 am IST (4.50 am GMT) but as usual, our build-up will begin in advance.

The players are leaving! The light is not conducive even for spin now. It's still not Stumps, officially. They are coming off for Bad Light. Very disappointing. But the safety of the players is paramount.
Slightly shorter and outside off, turning away but slow turn. Warner slaps it to covers. End of the first over and it is a good one for the Aussies.
Tossed up on middle, Warner lunges and blocks it out.
Off the inner half! On middle, Khawaja looks to drive, it goes more off the inner half through mid-wicket for one.
Two more! Shorter and outside off, Khawaja pushes it through covers and takes two.
Usman Khawaja and Australia are underway! Turn for Khan. This is flatter and on off, turns away. Khawaja looks to push at it, it goes more off the outer half through to third man for two.
Starts off with a flatter delivery, on off, Khawaja guides it to point.

Right then! That is it from the first Test! The teams head into the second Test on level terms and the action now shifts to Karachi for the next Test. The second Test of the series will begin on Saturday, 12th March and the first ball of Day 1 will be bowled at 10.30 am IST (5 am GMT). Do join us then and make sure you tune in early for the buildup. Until then, cheers and goodbye!

Babar Azam, the skipper of Pakistan, starts by crediting the way Imam played in both the innings. Adds, there are quite a few positives and they would like to continue that in the next game. Tells, the bowlers did well and the batters were excellent. Adds, the main bowlers will be available for the next game and that is a good thing.

Pat Cummins, the skipper of Australia, says that it was a great week in Rawalpindi and the whole city got around them and helped them out and it was great to be back after 24 years. Tells that they are relatively fresh going into the second Test and are looking forward to it.

Imam-ul-Haq is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for scoring hundred in both the innings. He says that he has been working hard for the last couple of years and he feels good to score centuries in both the innings, especially against a team like Australia. Tells that he was trying to do the basics right and just followed the process.
Stay tuned for the presentation.

Abdullah Shafique is up for a quick chat. He says it is a big thing for him to score a ton against Australia but he would love such runs overseas. Adds, he played the wrong shot in the first innings and then he spoke to the batting coach on how to improve. Mentions, it was a very good surface to bat on and he enjoyed batting on it. Ends by saying there were quite a few positives in this game and it was a good game for them.

Also, in a game which has moved so, so slow, the weather and the light also did not help. There was close to two sessions lost in totality. When the teams entered Day 5, Australia probably had more chances of winning than their opponents but something special was needed from their bowlers or Pakistan needed to collapse but it was the hosts' openers who stole the show with a massive, massive stand with both of them scoring tons and recording the highest ever opening stand for Pakistan in Test cricket against Australia.

In reply, the Aussie batters too cashed in, especially the top 4. Usman Khawaja and Marnus Labuschagne were dismissed in the 90s whereas Warner and Smith crossed 50s. Green too, made a handy contribution. However, unlike their opposition, the Pakistan bowlers did enjoy some success. Yes, they were made to toil hard but managed to get all 10 wickets on this placid wicket. Nauman Ali was the pick with a 6-fer and Shaheen Afridi too, bowled really well.

First it was Pakistan, after winning the toss and electing to bat, they posted close to 500, courtesy tons from Azhar Ali and Imam-ul-Haq. Yes, one would probably say they batted way too slowly but credit to the Australian bowlers in that part as they did not let Pakistan score freely. The visitors' pacers struggled to pick wickets but did not let the opposition run away with the game by letting them score at a good click.

The teams have decided to shake hands which means that is the end of the game and like expected, it has ended in a draw. Something special was needed for a result in this one from the bowlers but that was not to be. The wicket just did not deteriorate and it is yet another day dominated by the batters. The whole Test was about the batters. It was a road and both the sides enjoyed batting on it.

We are back for the final session of the first Test. The players have made their way out to the middle. Abdullah Shafique and Imam-ul-Haq are at the crease. Nathan Lyon will start with the ball for Australia. Here we go...
... Day 5, Session 3 ...

Pakistan continue to bat! The pair of Abdullah Shafique and Imam-ul-Haq has added 115 runs in the second session and they now lead by 208 runs! We saw some sign of intent towards the end of the session but really don't feel they are thinking of a declaration. So, if it wasn't quite obvious before, this Test match is surely going to end in a draw unless something very unlikely happens. It is all about milestones now. Both the openers will look to get to their tons after the break and then will cut loose. However, Pakistan will want the two to go on for as long as possible. Australia, clearly are happy to go ahead with their part-timers and give the pacers a rest. They too are probably looking to bowl the remaining overs as quickly as possible. 37 overs more to go in the last session, do join us for it. The final session of the Test begins at 3.45 pm IST (10.15 am GMT).
